{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f9384e5e-2b03-4358-915c-84f7c28d39c6","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:~/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30 seconds example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** — open it in Visual Studio, VS Code (with the .NET profiler extension), PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (convert first with `dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use the **sidecar approach**: run a `dotnet/sdk` container sharing the process namespace (`shareProcessNamespace: true`).\n- For always-on production diagnostics, consider enabling **EventPipe** via environment variables instead (`DOTNET_EnableEventPipe=1`).\n- `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` is a good quick sanity check before tracing to confirm CPU is actually spent in managed code.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8645d0e7-8938-4a73-8d82-32aab0106e50","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change request, so I'll answer directly.","outputTokens":435},"id":"31feddd0-4075-4451-8882-8c3d0b146fd6","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:51:36.240Z","parentId":"9893e8a8-577d-4bc5-b78b-bc9529b291fe"}
